The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 CBay Systems has acquired the accounts receivable amp; reimbursement management division of Certus Corporation, a US-based patient financial services company, for an undisclosed sum. The division delivers client-specific solutions for hospitals and physician groups based in the US. CBay has executed the acquisition through its group company Mirrus Systems Inc. Mirrus acquired all of the division?s technology platform and business assets in an all-cash deal.

 Mangalore Refinery and Petrochemicals Ltd is planning to award contracts for expansion of the refinery capacity to 15 million tonnes by third quarter this year. The ONGC board had approved a capital expenditure of Rs 8,000 crore to expand the refinery capacity from 9.69 million tonnes to 15 million tonnes per annum last month. 

 Paramount Communication Ltd has delayed the launch of its $15-million global depository receipts (GDR) issue. The lead manager of the issue has advised Paramount not to enter the market, on April 10, due to a technical objection raised by the Luxembourg Stock Exchange for listing.

 Efi has announced expansion plans for the Indian market. The three-year-old company, which moved its operations to a new facility in Bangalore, now employs 150 people and plans to ?greatly expand? its workforce during the current year.

 Dodsal Group has been awarded a contract of around Rs 4,300 crore ($951 million) by Qatar Petroleum for engineering, procuring, installing and commissioning of common cooling seawater system at Ras Laffan, Qatar.

 Oriental Bank of Commerce has announced change in interest rates for domestic term deposits. The hike in interest rate on deposit is in the range of 25 basis points to 75 basis points for domestic term deposits of less than Rs 15 lakh.

 Hispano Maghreb has begun to deliver urban buses to Casablanca?s urban transport operator, M?Dina Bus. The company had bagged the order to supply 800 buses to M?Dina in July last year.

 Katra Wilhelmsen Logistics Private Ltd launched the M. V. Goan Pride, which the company claims to be the first floating port in India. The port is 250 metre long and can store over 1,20,000 tonnes of cargo.

 Satyam School of Leadership has announced its partnership with Harvard Business School Publishing and Universities 21 Global to commence its ?best-in-class? curriculum.

